        "answer_count": 3,
        "title": "svg files rendering in android",
        "body": "<p>I wrote a program in Android for setting different kinds of images as my background image, but it is not working with svg files. I am not getting any errors, it is not displaying any image and I'm getting a blank screen in my emulator when using svg files. Can any one suggest how to read and display svg files in Android with some code? Or should I convert xml code?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 4141544,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "android",
            "svg"
        ],
        "score": 5,
        "accepted_answer_id": 4141570,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 9254,
        "last_edit_date": 1290673662
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d1152398d84f15b76eb25f13e825cda?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 55539,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 166339,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/166339/asaph",
                "reputation": 163505,
                "display_name": "Asaph"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 5,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1686295959,
            "creation_date": 1289367825,
            "body": "<p>Getting Batik to run on Android would involve a significant porting effort. There are easier ways to work with SVG on Android. See <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4517388/svg-processing-under-java-on-android-and-desktop/4644781#4644781\">this answer<\/a> and <a href=\"https://www.codeproject.com/Articles/130791/Android-ImageView-with-SVG-Support\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this post<\/a> for details.<\/p>\n<p>Batik uses Java2D to render SVG. Android does not support Java2D, and has its own custom graphics API instead. Batik likely won't work out-of-the-box on Android.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 4141570,
            "question_id": 4141544,
            "last_edit_date": 1686295959
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acbff12fdff1bb8bab766c31c366ef0f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 152374,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 366856,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/366856/jbeard4",
                "reputation": 12873,
                "display_name": "jbeard4",
                "accept_rate": 69
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1316024829,
            "creation_date": 1316024829,
            "body": "<p>If you can afford to only support Android versions greater than 3, then you could use a Webkit instance to render SVG, as the Android Webkit browser finally has SVG support compiled in.<\/p>\n\n<p>Alternatively, if you do not require support for scripting or animation, you try using this library: <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/svg-android/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://code.google.com/p/svg-android/<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 7421159,
            "question_id": 4141544
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd043aba9d97059108cbc719f73fc4a8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
